  "opinion": "As a mechanic from Bologna who's been around the shop for over forty years, I've never used social media. My kids and grandkids are the ones who do that stuff, but I've learned a lot from them about how the internet works. The first thing I'd say is to stay away from it altogether if you don't need to be there. If you do need to be on social media, make sure you're using a reliable platform with strong verification processes. I've seen too many people get scammed by fake accounts, so I recommend checking the account's history and making sure it's been active for a while. Also, don't share personal information like your address or phone number. If you see something that looks suspicious, don't click on it or share it with anyone. I've been a volunteer for the local community center for years and I know how important it is to protect people from scams. It's a shame that so many people are getting tricked by fake content these days, but with a bit of common sense and careful checking, you can avoid most of it. I'm not religious, so I don't have any faith in the internet's goodness, but I do believe that being careful and informed is the best way to stay safe.",
